# user-config.md template (session-handoff v0.1.0, schema 0.1)

This file is a **template**. The session-handoff skill renders it into your project space as `config/user-config.md` (or `config-user-config.md` on flat surfaces) on first invocation if you do not already have one. You then populate the `[tbd]` placeholders.

To configure interactively, load the rendered file and tell your AI "walk me through configuring this." It runs the shared interview (`references/configure.md`), uses the FIELD GUIDE below, and writes you a new version for approval before saving. The skill never silent-overwrites a config file.

Resolution order at runtime: `config/user-config.md` > `config/org-config.md` > skill defaults in `references/defaults.md`.

The rendered file is the content inside the fenced block below: everything from the `---` frontmatter through the final config key. On first run the skill auto-extracts exactly that fenced block (not this SPDX header or surrounding prose) and writes it as `config/user-config.md`. To do it by hand, copy everything inside the fence into `config/user-config.md` and fill the `[tbd]` fields:

```yaml
---
schema_version: "0.1"
_managed_by: session-handoff-skill
config_type: user
config_editable: true
configure_with: references/configure.md
---
# To configure: load this file and tell your AI "walk me through configuring this."
# It runs the shared interview (references/configure.md), uses the FIELD GUIDE below,
# and writes you a new version of this file for approval before saving.
#
# ============================================================
# session-handoff - user configuration (v0.1.0, schema 0.1)
# ============================================================
# Populate the [tbd] fields. Fields with values shown are skill
# defaults; override them only if you want different behavior.
# Reload by re-uploading this file to your project space.
# ============================================================


# -----------------------------------------------------------
# FIELD GUIDE: operator
# -----------------------------------------------------------
# Identity used in the audit block the skill writes
# (audit.approved_by). It is self-asserted, NOT platform-verified
# (see references/schema.md section 4.1).
#
# primary_name (REQUIRED): your name as you want it on handoffs
#   you approve. The skill does not pull this from the platform;
#   you declare it here.
# preferred_aliases (OPTIONAL): short-forms the skill may use
#   when space is tight.
# -----------------------------------------------------------
operator:
  primary_name: "[tbd]"
  preferred_aliases: []


# -----------------------------------------------------------
# FIELD GUIDE: defaults
# -----------------------------------------------------------
# Cross-project defaults applied when not overridden by
# org-config or chat-time instructions.
#
# preferred_platform (REQUIRED): the surface you use as your
#   primary destination. Drives the destination-aware length
#   budget (config/platform-parameters.md).
#   One of: claude-ai | claude-code | cowork |
#           chatgpt-enterprise | m365-copilot
# -----------------------------------------------------------
defaults:
  preferred_platform: "claude-ai"


# -----------------------------------------------------------
# FIELD GUIDE: conventions
# -----------------------------------------------------------
# Stylistic conventions for skill-generated content. Skill
# defaults shown; override only to diverge.
#
# date_format: ISO 8601 date format. "YYYY-MM-DD" is the
#   default and only supported value in v0.1.0.
# filename_slug_style: slug style for skill-generated
#   filenames. "kebab-case" is the default.
# em_dashes_allowed: whether the skill may use em dashes in
#   generated prose. Default false.
# preferred_table_density: how tightly the skill packs tables
#   in operator-facing output. One of: high | medium | low
# default_response_register: tonal register for operator-facing
#   prose. One of: strategic-peer | professor | collaborative
# -----------------------------------------------------------
conventions:
  date_format: "YYYY-MM-DD"
  filename_slug_style: "kebab-case"
  em_dashes_allowed: false
  preferred_table_density: "high"
  default_response_register: "strategic-peer"


# -----------------------------------------------------------
# FIELD GUIDE: privacy  (COMPLIANCE-RELEVANT)
# -----------------------------------------------------------
# Privacy posture applied to skill-written handoffs. Changes
# here are flagged as compliance-relevant in the configure
# interview (references/configure.md section 6).
#
# default_sensitivity: the default sensitivity label stamped on
#   new handoffs unless overridden by org-config or chat-time
#   instruction. One of: open | internal | confidential | restricted
# sanitization_prompt: when the BLOCKING sanitize question
#   fires. The locked sanitization-surfacing line always emits
#   regardless of this setting. One of:
#     always    - fire on every invocation (stricter enterprises set this)
#     on-signal - fire when sharing or sensitive content is
#                 detected (default)
#     never     - never fire the blocking question
# pii_flagging_enabled: whether assistive PII flagging runs.
#   Default true (the one secure-by-default exception). PII
#   flagging is assistive and never claims completeness.
# -----------------------------------------------------------
privacy:
  default_sensitivity: "internal"
  sanitization_prompt: "on-signal"
  pii_flagging_enabled: true


# -----------------------------------------------------------
# FIELD GUIDE: contact
# -----------------------------------------------------------
# Where feedback about the skill's behavior should be routed.
# Free-form: a URL, email, channel, or null.
# -----------------------------------------------------------
contact:
  feedback_channel: "[tbd]"
```

## Required fields

The following are REQUIRED and must be populated before the rendered `user-config.md` is considered complete:

- `operator.primary_name`
- `defaults.preferred_platform`

A rendered file with any required field still `[tbd]` is permitted (the skill operates with placeholder values) but pre-flight notes: "user-config.md has unpopulated required fields: [list]. Populate to complete personalization."

## What does not belong in user-config.md

- Anything specific to a single session; use chat-time instructions.
- Anything that changes schema validity. The fields above are the schema 0.1 contract for `config_type: user`.
- Secrets or credentials. The skill does not need them, and config files may end up in shared infrastructure.

## Cross-skill convention

This file's format (markdown with a YAML body, kebab-case keys, every field documented with rationale, a single shared interview procedure) is part of the config-layer convention shared with the sister skill project-context and proposed as a cross-skill standard. See `README.md`.
